note: Maxx impressed in Week 4, tallying five solos, three tackles for loss, one forced fumble, one interception, and three passes defended. Crosby has just two sacks on the season but seven tackles for loss, one pick, one forced fumble, and four passes defended. Colts Week 5.

Aidan went off in Week 4, reeling off four solos, two assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Hutchinson has started to heat up for the Lions, with all four of his sacks coming in his last three games. Treat Aidan as a top-five option for a tasty Week 5 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Danielle Hunter was excellent in Week 4, racking up three solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Hunter is known to get sacks in bunches and has been no different this season, with all four of his sacks coming in two contests. Hunter is an easy DL1 play for Week 5, especially now that it looks like it will be Cooper Rush under center for the Baltimore Ravens. Start Hunter everywhere.

Granderson was excellent in Week 4, tallying five solos, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Granderson has been rolling to start the season and is now up to 4.5 sacks on the season (second in the NFL). He has notched at least one sack in three of his four contests and has an excellent opportunity to add more to his ledger in Week 5, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Giants.

Verse was excellent in Week 4, reeling off four solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Verse has recorded a sack in back-to-back games and is up to two sacks on the season. Tap Verse as a top-25 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Byron Young was at it again in Week 4, tallying two solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Young is tied with Brian Burns for the league lead with five sacks and has also recorded a sack in every game this season. There is no reason not to include him among the top-10 options for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs. Start him with confidence.

Buckner showed up in Week 4, reeling off four solos, four assists, and two tackles for loss. DeForest has zero sacks on the season but has stayed active in the solo department, recording three or more solos in three straight. Buckner is still an easy DT1 play, but is more of a low-end DL2 during the byes tha
n the top-20 option we are used to viewing him as. Adjust expectations, but start him with confidence for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Furious George was at it again in Week 4, racking up two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Karlaftis has recorded a sack in three of his four contests and needs to be viewed as a DL2 option, at least until he cools down. Treat him as such for a plus matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars in Week 5.

Simmons manhandled the Texans' offensive line to the tune of four solos, one assist, one sack, and four tackles for loss. Simmons remains a DT1 play but should be viewed as more of a DL3 than a DL2. Treat him as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Leonard Williams was excellent in Week 4, tallying three solos, one assist, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Williams has at least a half sack in three straight games and is up to 2.5 sacks on the season.  Continue to treat him as a DT1/DL2 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Latu was excellent in Week 4, tallying three solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Laiatu has disappointed relative to expectations, as the sack was just his first of the season. Latu remains a high upside play but should be viewed as more of a low-end DL3 play for Week 5. Add Latu where pass rush help is needed, especially for those looking for bye week help.

Tuli had a game for the ages in Week 4, going nuclear with seven solos, three assists, four sacks, five tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. As good as Jaxson Dart looked in spurts or on SportsCenter, this game was the Tuli breakout show. Tuipulotu was a bit of a disappointment relative to expectations heading into this game, but the explosion puts him in the DL2 mix for the byes. Tap him as a DL2/3 for a plus Week 5 matchup against Washington.

Joey Bosa was excellent in Week 4, racking up one solo, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Bosa is up to two sacks on the season and is playing a larger role than expected, so roll with him as a low-end DL3 play for Week 5 and beyond. Tap him as a top-36 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Josh Sweat was at it again in Week 4, racking up two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Sweat has a sack in three straight games and is sitting pretty with three sacks on the season. He will continue to see heavy snaps for Arizona and should be treated as a borderline DL2 option as long as he is cooking. Make the add where possible.

Calais impressed in Week 4, reeling off two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Calais has started hot for the Cardinals, recording a sack in two of his last three and now sits at three sacks on the season. His strong play has put him back in the DT1 conversation and also makes him a high upside DL3 target for Week 5, thanks to a tasty matchup against Cam Ward and the Tennessee Titans.

Redmond showed up in Week 4, tallying two solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Redmond has impressed through four weeks of play, notching a sack in two of his last three games, sitting at three sacks on the season (11th in the league, tied for first among defensive tackles). Redmond has been as good as advertised this season and is making a case to be viewed as a top-five DT option. Start Redmond wherever possible for a tasty Week 5 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Cam Jordan showed up in Week 4, racking up four solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Cam is up to 2.5 sacks on the season and is an easy DL3 option during the byes. He will have  DL2 appeal in the right matchups, such as the one he has in Week 5 special against Jaxson Dart and the New York Giants. Start Jordan wherever possible.

Vita Vea showed out in Week 4, racking up three solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. The sacks were his first two of the season, and Vea is more of a run stuffer and pressure creator than a sack artist. Stash him in case he ge
ts hot, but keep him benched for Week 5 against Seattle unless you are looking for a DT2 option. Look elsewhere for your Week 5 DL3/DT2

Darius Robinson showed up in Week 4, racking up two solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Robinson had not done much prior to this past weekend, with the sack being his first of the season. Darius has put himself on the DL4 radar for the byes and is still a strong dynasty stash, but should remain on benches for Week 5 despite the saliva-inducing matchup against Cam Ward and the Tennessee Titans.

Drake Thomas showed up in Week 4, racking up four solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Thomas benefitted from an expanded role with Demarcus hurt and was able to notch his first sack of the season. Thomas has recorded four solos in back-to-back outings and is slowly earning the coaching staff's trust over Tyrice Knight due to the latter's issues in pass coverage. Keep Drake benched for now, but make the speculative stash him everywhere. Look elsewhere for your Week 5 LB3/4.

Nick Cross has been rolling for the Colts, reeling off six solos, five assists, and 0.5 sacks in Week 4. He has recorded five or more solos in three straight contests while chipping in a cool 1.5 sacks on the season. Continue to trust him as a DB1 option for Week 5.

Curl impressed in Week 4, racking up three solos, six assists, two interceptions, and three passes defended. Curl has been producing at a DB1 level for IDP managers, generating five or more solos in three of his four contests, while adding two picks and a sack on the season. Tap Kam as a top-10 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Tykee was back at it in Week 4, tallying five solos, four assists, and two passes defended. Tykee has recorded four or more solos in each of his contests so far this season and has chipped in at least one pass defended in three of four. Treat him as a DB2 option during byes, including this week against the Seattle Seahawks. Start Tykee wherever possible.

Love returned from injury and posted six solos and one pass defended in Week 4. Love is a DB1 option when healthy and should be treated as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Cooper DeJean impressed in Week 4, racking up eight solos, one assist, and two passes defended. DeJean has recorded five or more solos in three straight, forcing himself into the DB2 conversation for the byes in the process. Treat him as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Dax impressed in Week 4, tallying five solos, four assists, and one pass defended. Dax has been rolling to start the season, recording five or more solos in three of his four contests. Tap Dax as a high-end DB2 option for what should be a busy afternoon against a potent Detroit Lions offense. Start him everywhere.

Lake impressed in Week 4, racking up five solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Lake had a slower start to the season, but has recorded four or more solos in two of his four contests. With that said, he is more of a mid-tier DB2 than the elite DB2 option we were expecting. Still, he makes for a strong DB2 option for Week 5, thanks to the byes being here and a plus matchup against the San Francisco 49ers. Start Lake everywhere.

Devon returned to the field in Week 4, tallying five solos, four assists, and 0.5 sacks. Witherspoon has recorded five solos in both of his games played and remains a strong CB1/DB3 option, bye week or not. Plug him into lineups wherever possible for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Sigle showed up in Week 4, tallying six solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Sigle has now recorded five or more solos in two of his four contests, putting him in the DB3 mix for the byes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 5 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Craig Woodson was excellent in Week 4, generating four solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss. Woodson has emerged as the only S option on the Patriots now that Jaylinn Hawkins and Kyle Dugger are splitting time, cannibalizing each other's fantasy values in the process. For his part, Woodson has recorded four or more solos in three of his four contests and is cementing himself as a solid DB3 option. Woodson has DB2 upside for Week 5, thanks to a projected busy night against the Buffalo Bills on Sunday Night Football. Start Woodson where possible.

Bishop was excellent in Week 4, racking up four solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Bishop has recorded four solos in each of his four contests this season, adding a sack or pick in two of those four. Tap Bishop as a DB3 option for a plus Week 5 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Sainstrill impressed in Week 4, tallying three solos, four assists, one interception, and one pass defended. He has solidified himself as a strong CB2 play with his production thus far but remains a strong avoid as DB play for Week 5, even with a potential plus matchup on tap against the Los Angeles Chargers. Let him show some more consistency before sliding him into lineups over other higher-floor options.

Sanker was excellent in Week 4, tallying four solos, one assist, one interception, and three passes defended. Sanker has recorded four or more solos in two of his three starts, putting himself on the DB3 map for the byes. He has a tasty Week 5 matchup against the New York Giants, making him an upside play for those needing a bye week filler. Make the add and start where needed.

Dru showed up in Week 4, notching two solos, one interception, and four passes defended. Phillips has been playing at a CB1 level and has worked his way into the DB3 conversation on the strength of two spike weeks in his first four contests. Treat him as such for a tasty Week 5 matchup against the New Orleans Saints. Start him where possible.

Quinyon impressed in Week 4, racking up four solos, one assist, and five passes defended. Mitchell has been solid to start the season, at least by CB standards, recording three or more solos in each. He does have CB1 upside and should be started where possible in CB leagues, but for the rest of us, he should be left on benches. Look elsewhere for your Week 5 DB3/4.

Tre'Davious White showed up in Week 4, racking up seven solos and a tackle for loss. White is undergoing somewhat of a career resurgence in Buffalo and can be trusted as a CB2/DB4 option for the byes.
